[4] Interview with Margaret Chan, WHO
Date: Wed 14 Oct 2015
Source: Science Insider [edited]
http://news.sciencemag.org/health/2015/10/wake-ebola-epidemic-margaret-chan-wants-countries-put-their-money-where-their-mouth


Science Insider reports on an interview with Margaret Chan, director-general of the World Health Organization (WHO) by Kai Kupferschmidt, contributing correspondent for Science magazine based in Berlin, Germany; she responds to the criticism that has been directed at WHO concerning its handling of the Ebola outbreak.

She discussed the delay in declaring Ebola a Public Health Emergency of International Concern: "Information was not flowing up. That is a big problem. You cannot manage what you don't see and what you don't know. I think all of us underestimated the context of these countries. An old disease in a new context gave us surprises."

She discussed the disproportionate restrictions on travel to and from the Ebola region imposed by 34 countries against the recommendations of WHO: That is part of the "International Health Regulations [IHR], an international treaty with the good intention of building a collective defense system against a common threat. But the implementation of the IHR is very poor; there is a lot of disincentive. Why should I report? The minute I report, you impose a trade ban and travel ban on me. That is why we need to review the IHR and change them to provide incentive instead of disincentive."

Recommendations to change the IHR in the Report of the Ebola Interim Assessment Panel led by Barbara Stocking were not implemented because of lack of resources. Chan said: "That is why the Stocking report made another recommendation: Health cannot be left in the hands of ministries of health alone. It has to escalate so that heads of state, heads of government, will consider the social, financial, and human costs of non-action." ...-more

