[5] Suspected, research, funding
14 Oct 2015 Nigeria: Ebola: First Consultant Hospital Laments Low Patronage
http://www.leadership.ng/news/466955/ebola-first-consultant-hospital-laments-low-patronage
[Nigeria may have been declared Ebola-free, but at the First Consultants Hospital in Lagos, where [an] Ebola virus disease patient was taken after becoming ill on arrival in Lagos, stigmatisation is the order of the day.

The Chief Medical Director, First Consultant Hospital Centre, Professor Benjamin Ohiaeri, in an interview with LEADERSHIP, said the hospital still battles to regain the trust of patients, adding that the hospital has been deserted since the Ebola outbreak.

Ohiaeri said the hospital spent a lot of money in replacing every piece of potentially contaminated equipment, from the emergency room and laboratory to washing machines in the laundry.

He said the hospital may be open and immaculately clean, but patient numbers are still down, while some of the doctors and nurses who survived Ebola are still treated with mistrust.]

12 Oct 2015 Sierra Leone: Earlier bed delivery could have halved Sierra Leone Ebola outbreak - experts
http://www.trust.org/item/20151012185547-ecykw/?source=fiOtherNews2
[According to new research published in the Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, the early supplying of thousands of Ebola treatment beds by the UK and Sierra Leone governments, and NGOs, enabled isolation of patients. This prevented an estimated 57 000 Ebola virus disease (EVD) cases and 40 000 deaths in Sierra Leone. The study shows the large impact of local and international involvement early on produced a substantial decrease in transmission of Ebola virus disease (EVD). Providing the beds one month earlier could have halved the number of EVD cases.]

12 Oct 2015 UK: Ebola-infected nurse's family and friends given unlicensed vaccine after her relapse
http://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/ebola-infected-nurse-pauline-cafferkeys-6621592
[Approximately 58 of PC's friends, family and contacts (some of whom are health-care workers) have been checked by medics. NHS Greater Glasgow and Clyde (GGCH) said 40 people were confirmed as having had direct contact with PC's bodily fluids. They were offered an unlicensed vaccine; 25 accepted, 15 either declined or had medical conditions which precluded receiving the vaccine.]

[Unfortunately, it is most likely those medically compromised individuals who were not eligible for the vaccine who are most at risk, i.e., who most need protection. - Mod.LK]

13 Oct 2015 UK: Lab staff at Glasgow hospital told NOT to leave the country over Ebola fears
http://www.eveningtimes.co.uk/news/13842874.Ebola_fears_for_laboratory_staff_at_Glasgow_hospital/
[The lab workers at Queen Elizabeth Community Hospital, where patient PC was admitted last week, have claimed they were not informed of the lab samples' potentially infectious source (PC), and may not have used appropriate personal protective equipment (PPE). There are concerns these lab workers were exposed to PC's bodily fluids. The lab workers were told not to leave the country and to daily monitor their temperature.]

Vaccines, research
------------
12 Oct 2015: GeneXpert Ebola assay for diagnosis of Ebola virus disease performs well in field tests
http://www.hcplive.com/conference-coverage/idweek-2015/genexpert-ebola-assay-for-diagnosis-of-ebola-virus-disease-performs-well-in-field-tests
[Recent studies suggest the Cepheid GeneXpert Ebola assay performs well using whole blood and buccal swab samples submitted for routine testing for the Ebola virus.]

13 Oct 2015: China-made Ebola vaccine permitted for overseas trial
http://www.ndtv.com/world-news/china-made-ebola-vaccine-permitted-for-overseas-trial-1231534
[A restructured Ebola vaccine independently developed by China has entered Phase II clinical trials in Sierra Leone. This is the vaccine's 1st overseas clinical trial permit.]

12 Oct 2015 Contamination of Health Care Personnel During Removal of Personal Protective Equipment
http://archinte.jamanetwork.com/article.aspx?articleid=2457400
[Myreen E. Tomas, MD; Sirisha Kundrapu, MD; Priyaleela Thota, M et al. 2015. Contamination of Health Care Personnel During Removal of Personal Protective Equipment. _JAMA Internal Medicine_. [edited]

[IMPORTANCE. Contamination of the skin and clothing of health care personnel during removal of personal protective equipment (PPE) contributes to dissemination of pathogens and places personnel at risk for infection.

OBJECTIVES. To determine the frequency and sites of contamination on the skin and clothing of personnel during PPE removal and to evaluate the effect of an intervention on the frequency of contamination.

DESIGN, SETTING, AND PARTICIPANTS. We conducted a point-prevalence study and quasi-experimental intervention from 28 Oct 2014, through 31 Mar 2015. Data analysis began 17 Nov 2014, and ended 21 Apr 2015. Participants included a convenience sample of health care personnel from 4 Northeast Ohio hospitals who conducted simulations of contaminated PPE removal using fluorescent lotion and a cohort of health care personnel from 7 study units in one medical center that participated in a quasi-experimental intervention that included education and practice in removal of contaminated PPE with immediate visual feedback based on fluorescent lotion contamination of skin and clothing.

MAIN OUTCOMES AND MEASURES. The primary outcomes were the frequency and sites of contamination on skin and clothing of personnel after removal of contaminated gloves or gowns at baseline vs. after the intervention. A secondary end point focused on the correlation between contamination of skin with fluorescent lotion and bacteriophage MS2, a nonpathogenic, nonenveloped virus. ...-more]

12 Oct 2015 The Increasing Visibility of the Threat of Health Care Worker Self-contamination
http://archinte.jamanetwork.com/article.aspx?articleid=2457398
[Michelle Doll, MD; Gonzalo M. Bearman, MD, MPH . The Increasing Visibility of the Threat of Health Care Worker Self-contamination . _JAMA Internal Medicine_. [edited]
The vulnerability of health care workers to acquisition and propagation of infectious agents has received global attention because of recent outbreaks of highly communicable and fatal diseases, including Ebola virus disease and severe acute respiratory syndrome. The emergence of these high-profile pathogens has prompted calls for better personal protective equipment (PPE), specifically, masks, gowns, and gloves, to protect health care workers and patients. In this issue of JAMA Internal Medicine, Tomas and colleagues provide a timely addition to the existing literature on the limitations of our current PPE.

In a series of related studies that use previously described methods to simulate contaminated PPE, the investigators convincingly document a high frequency of health care worker self contamination when using PPE. The bulk of their data come from 435 simulations of donning and/or doffing of gowns and gloves contaminated with a fluorescent lotion: 234 were soiled glove simulations, and 201 were soiled gown simulations. Almost half (46.0 per cent) of these simulations resulted in health care worker self-contamination of skin or clothing. ...-more]

14 Oct 2015: Preliminary study finds that Ebola virus fragments can persist in the semen of some survivors for at least 9 months
http://www.cdc.gov/media/releases/2015/p1014-ebola-virus.html
[According to findings published in the New England Journal of Medicine, preliminary results of a study into persistence of Ebola virus in body fluids show that some men still produce semen samples that test positive for Ebola virus 9 months after onset of symptoms.

This study provides the 1st results of a long-term study being jointly conducted by the Sierra Leone Ministry of Health and Sanitation, the World Health Organization and the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.
Citation: Mate S, Kugelman J, et al. (14 Oct 2015). Molecular Evidence of Sexual Transmission of Ebola Virus. _New England Journal of Medicine_. DOI: 10.1056/NEJMoa1509773]

14 Oct 2015: 1st known case of sexually transmitted Ebola reported
https://www.sciencenews.org/blog/science-ticker/first-known-case-sexually-transmitted-ebola-reported
[A Liberian woman contracted Ebola virus disease (EVD) in March [2015] by having sex with a survivor of EVD, researchers report. Using studies of both people's viral genomes and of their contacts with any other possible sources of the virus, the researchers conclude the woman's disease represents the 1st known case of sexual transmission of EVD. The transmission occurred 155 days after his 2nd test for the presence of Ebola virus in the blood showed him to be clear of the virus.

The genomes of the Ebola virus from the man's semen and woman's blood were not only practically identical but also different from all other Western African Ebola viruses that had been sequenced.

Citation: Mate S, Kugelman J, et al. (14 Oct 2015). Molecular Evidence of Sexual Transmission of Ebola Virus. _New England Journal of Medicine_. DOI: 10.1056/NEJMoa1509773]

14 Oct 2015: Ebola drug killed by congressional inaction less than 2 years before outbreak
http://www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/next/body/ebola-drug-halted/
[A decade before the 2014 Ebola epidemic, the United States Department of Defense (USDOD) started a research program that eventually produced a promising drug to treat Ebola virus disease (EVD), one that was fast-tracked for review by the Food and Drug Administration (FDA). Then, in late 2012, a year and a half before the 1st case of EVD was reported in West Africa, the program was abruptly halted, the victim of political brinksmanship in the United States Congress.

In 2004, there was a close call when a scientist working with mice and the Ebola virus suffered a needlestick injury, which triggered a search for a treatment in case the scientist tested positive. Sarepta Therapeutics was able to, over a weekend, synthesize several compounds which were enough to treat the scientist, who didn't contract EVD after all.

This close call triggered the search for a treatment for EVD. By 2010, Sarepta had a USD 291 million contract for the advanced development of the company's virus therapeutic candidates for Ebola and Marburg, a similar hemorrhagic fever.

In 2012, Sarepta Therapeutics became the 1st Ebola drug candidate to be given fast-track designation by the FDA, a designation meant to expedite the review of a drug that addresses a serious condition and fills an unmet medical need. One month later, as Congress was locked in a standoff over the debt ceiling and the federal government faced austere budget cuts, development of the promising Ebola treatment was suddenly halted.]

[A good example of why research funding must be maintained even in times when an outbreak is not occurring. - Mod.LK]

